[We are very grateful for Dr Vosloo's expedient response to our posting
20040423.1126. We hope her good advice will be urgently followed.
Detailed sampling directions, including methods of collection, transport
fluids, and temperature during transportation are described in detail in
OIE's Manual <http://oie.int/eng/normes/mmanual/A_00022.htm>. For
laboratory diagnosis, the tissue of choice is epithelium. Ideally, at least
1 g of epithelial tissue should be collected from an unruptured or recently
ruptured vesicle.
Where epithelial tissue is not available from ruminant animals, for example
in advanced or convalescent cases, or where infection is suspected in the
absence of clinical signs, samples of OP fluid can be collected by means of
a probang (sputum) cup. - Mod.AS]
